Why is compaction important?

Civil engineering projects requires earthwork, movements of earthen materials from one site to another. Compaction is essential to increase the bearing capacity or strength of soils and to significantly reduce the future settlements.

Soil compaction

Is a form of soil improvement that consists of increasing soil's density using dynamic or vibratory loads.

Benefits of soil compaction:

  • Increased soil strength.
  • Lower compressibility.
  • Reduction of water flow.
  • Increased soil stability.
  • Reduction in frost damage.

  3. Water

Soil fabric

It denotes the unique geometric arrangement of particles, particle groups, and pore spaces in a soil.
  • Defines how strong the soil is because it configures force chains.
  • Affects the capacity of water to percolate trough the soil matrix.
  • Difficult to measure directly.

Relative density

\(D_r\): Measures the packing of coarse soils comparing their void ratio relative to the maximum and minimum possible densities. This measurement is a proxy for the soil fabric of clean coarse soils.
\(D_r= \cfrac{e_{max}-e}{e_{max}-e_{min}} \times 100\)
  • \(e_{max}\) is the maximum possible void ratio (ASTM D4253).
  • \(e_{min}\) is the minimum possible void ratio (ASTM D4253).

Quiz 3.2

What is the relative density of a sand in its densest state?
  1. 50%
  2. <0%
  3. 0%
  4. 100%
  5. >100%

Compaction of loose coarse soils

When \(e=e_{min}\) the soil is at its densest state and \(D_r=100\%\). Densification of coarse soils aims to increase the relative density.
  • For coarse materials, soils with low \(D_r\) are referred as to loose soils. Otherwise, they are dense soils.
  • For coarse soils, densification is achieved by vibration.
  • Reaching \(D_r=100\%\) or \(D_r=0\%\) is virtually impossible.
Note: The reason why it is virtually impossible to achieve max and min densities is that both would require a high level of organization of millions of particles.

Example 3.1

Calculate the relative density of uniform spherical particles when their void ratio is 0.5. What is the maximum and minimum dry densities of such soil? Assume \(G_s=2.65\)

Proctor test (ASTM D1140, D1557)

Used to obtain the maximum dry unit weight \(\gamma_{d,max}\) and the optimum water content \(w_{opt}\) for certain compaction effort.
  • Soil is pour into a container of known volume in layers.
  • A standard hammer delivers the compaction effort to the soil.
  • The process is repeated with soils having different water contents.

Compaction effort

\(E_{comp}\): Is the total energy per unit of volume delivered to the soil to compact it.
\(E_{comp}=m_h g \cfrac{h_d N_b N_l}{V}\)
  • \(m_h=\) Hammer mass.
  • \(h_d=\) drop height.
  • \(N_b=\) number of blows per layer.
  • \(N_l=\) number of layers.
  • \(V=\) Volume of mold.
Note: Part of this energy dissipates as heat due to friction. Compaction is achieved by forcing air out, particles rearrangement, and particle breakage.

Example 3.2

Find the compaction effort of a Proctor test knowing \(h_d=45.7\)cm, \(m_h=4.54\)kg, \(N_b=25\), \(N_l=5\). Compute the result in lb-ft/ft3 and kJ/m3. The volume of the compacted soil is 943 cm3

Theoretical maximum dry density

An expression relating the dry unit weight \(\gamma_{d}\) with the water content \(w\) can be found using phase relationships.

\(\gamma_d=\cfrac{\gamma_w G_s}{1+wG_s/S}\)

\(\gamma_d\) is maximized if \(S=100\%\) (i.e., all air is removed)

It is the line resulting from the theoretical maximum dry density of the soil.
\(\gamma_{d,max}=\cfrac{\gamma_w G_s}{1+wG_s}\)

Example 3.3

Find the maximum dry density of a soil compacted with 6% of water content and \(G_s=2.66\). Plot the ZAV and lines of equal saturation at 80% and 60%.

Quiz 3.3

Which of the following compaction efforts will produce the smallest \(w_{opt}\)?
  1. 1,200 kJ/m3
  2. 2,400 kJ/m3
  3. 3,000 kJ/m3
  4. 15,000 kJ/m3
  5. Is the same for all
Why is the compaction curve a parabola?
  • Dry of optimum fabric is flocculated. Water destroy the floccules macropores.
  • Wet of optimum fabric is disperse. Water swells the fabric.
  • Compaction on the wet side is better for expansive soils.
  • Soils compacted on the dry side are more permeable than soils compacted in the wet side.

Compaction specifications

  1. End Product specs: A relative compaction is specified and the contractor finds the means to achieve that goal.
  2. Method specs: All methods to compact the soil are specified, like a recipe.
\(RC:\) Is the percentage of compaction achieved in the field with respect to a max. dry density obtained in a Proctor test.
\(RC[\%]=\cfrac{\gamma_{d \ \mathrm{field}}}{\gamma_{d, max}} \times 100\)
Do not confuse relative compaction with relative density. They are not the same.

Example 3.5
